"font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Transport Select Committee</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (TSC)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">further wo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rk must</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> be undertaken</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to ensure that the innocent accident victim is not disadvantaged</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> put off from making a genuine claim following an ac</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cident that was not their fault or have their </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ability to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">access justice compromised.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Through our discussions with the ABI and medical reporting organisations, MASS has agreed in principle </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a proposal which has been submitted to the Mi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nistry of Justice outlining</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> an improved process for medical evidence and the accreditation of medical exp</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">erts. We have also for over two years been involved in discussions with the ABI on data sharing between claimant law firms and insurers and how this would assist with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> tackling fraud. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We are hopeful that substantive progress can be made on this in the near </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">future. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">MASS believes that data sharing will be particularly effective </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">against </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">opportunistic fraudsters, as claimant solicitors would be able to identify at an early stage inconsistent or inaccurate information given to them.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">MASS welcomes the Government’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s announcement not to raise the small claims limit. Following so much</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> recent</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> reform, and more</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> still</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to come, it is vital that the personal injury </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sector</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is allowed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a period </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">implement the current changes, understand the inevitable changes in market behav</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">iour, analyse the impact of the existing reforms and fully understand their unforeseen and unintended consequences. We believe that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a full and detailed review</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of the reforms should</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> be undertaken </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">efore any further change</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> considered.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Comments on the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">TSC Letter to the Ministry of Justice</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">2008-09 data </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">– </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is imperative that policy is based upon solid and reliable evidence. Accurate and current data has historically proven to be difficult to access and we would strongly support all efforts to improve </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the quality and usefulness of available data to aid understanding of the market. We would make the following observations about the 2008-09 data:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">When using data from any source it is important to recognise that strict parameters are r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">equired along with m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ore detailed definitions. When making any comparisons of data, it is imperative that such data is ‘like for like’. Other points to bear in mind include:</span></li></ul><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The word “whiplash” is not always used; th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e injury may be referred</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">instance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">soft-tissue </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">injury</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In multiple injury claims whiplash may be just one element among</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">st</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> others</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Injuries are reported to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Compensation Recovery Unit (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">CRU</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> before the medico-legal report is prepared and the initial summary provided to the CRU (which is the only infor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">mation  ever provided) is simply intended to be a brief indication of the nature of the injury</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Consideration needs to be given to the percentage of road acci</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">dents where one </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">or more </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">person</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> present with a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n injury. A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2005 Glasgow A &amp; E report suggested</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">figure of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> around 39% - a more informative figure on which to assess trends an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d understand the nature of injuries</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We suggest insurers are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">questioned</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">number of claims presented – not all injuries are reported to the police and police do not reco</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rd accidents where there is no immediate evidence of injury, so</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> we believe that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> police data </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is of questionable value and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">should not be used</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">More information</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is needed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> from other jurisdictions in Europe to assist in drawing coherent conclusions from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">international </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">data – we have no way of knowing for example whether reports that 31% of injury claims in France are for whiplash</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> are based upon the comparable definitions of the injury</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> used in England &amp; Wales</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Standard medical report</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">MASS agree that s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ome s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ections of the report should be standardised, in particular the sections that we anticipate will be used as part of the medical expert accreditation process, e.g. prognosis, rehab recommendations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">But we believe i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t is inappropriate that the report should b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e wholly in standard form;  individuals suffer in very different ways from similar accidents and injuries, and the medical evidence needs to reflect this, particularly in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Claims Portal </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">process.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Whilst there may be advantages, inevitably t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he more standa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rdised the report, the more scope there is for a fraudster to provide</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a ‘standard’ level of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">information</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Please </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">also </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">see </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">attached</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the cross industry paper provided to the MoJ on medical expert accreditation; further work on this is under way, but this</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is a complex process and it is important that it be properly thought through</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> before implementation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  We feel that the MoJ’s 12 month estimate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for development</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is realistic, and if, as seems likely, some elements of the changes will have to be written into </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the Claims Portal process, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">it would appear to be appropriate that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">implementation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> be part of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">new Portal </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">when it </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is launched in 2015.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Provision of information and attending medical practitioners</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Requiring injured claimants to see a medical</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> practitioner after an accident</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ould put an unnecessary burden on the NHS </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">without providing substantive proof of an injury</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">; fraudsters would </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">likely </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">be more aware of the requirement than genuine claimants and would ensure that they attended their GP. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">round 2005 the BMA </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">provided</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> guidance through the Law Society that solicitors should stop advising clients to go to their GP because of this very issue; the advice should be that clients should see their GP only if they feel the need to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> rather than as an au</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tomatic part of the process</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A ban on pre-medical offers and the proposed reforms to the medical expert accreditation process should drive out the poor behaviour associated with having little or no evidence to support a claim without putting a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n unnecessary</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> burden on the NHS</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Analyse impact of Portal</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We welcome the TSC’s comments on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ne</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ed to assess the impact of the P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ortal and the costs reductions brought by the Portal process before reconsidering increasing the small claims track. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In the ABI Key </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Insurance Facts 2012, £9.3 billion was paid out in motor claims (£7.1 billion on private vehicles and £2.2 on commercial)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">With the changes introduced in April 2013, they have achieved savings of at least £1.3 billion</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Accordingly payments made by insurers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> immediately reduced  by 12%</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Very significant fur</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ther savings will be achieved following</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the July 2013 reforms introducing fixed fees across the fast track (all claims up to £25,000)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is imperative that the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Government undertakes a full and thorough ana</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lysis, using sound evidence and data from all </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">stakeholders within the process, to assess the functioning of the Portal</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Small Claims Limit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline"> (SCL)</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">MASS believes that not raising the SCL was the correct decision. Although frequently dismissed as an argument,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> we continue to firmly believe that raising the SCL would seriously impact upon the ability of innocent accident victims to have access to the justice that they deserve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In addition to assessing the Portal amendments and cost reductions, consideration must</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> be given with regard to obtaining and understanding medical evidence by a litigant in person</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (LIP)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Not only will they have to pay for a medical report up front at a cost of up to £240, but they would then need to understand the findings and terminology o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">f the report and accurately assess the amount of compensation to claim.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Significant and very real</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> incidents of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">injustice would </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">undoubtedly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">occur </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">were</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a LIP</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> be left</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to pursue their own claim with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">only </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">limit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ed knowledge and understanding </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of expert / medical</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> evidence and the overall claim,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> against an insurer, who will have access to a representative.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Consequently providing a routine submission of expert evidence should not be seen as an opportunity to raise the small claims limit.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">If the small claims limit is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> increased, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">history  has shown that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">there will be an increase in the number of claims management companies </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">fill the gap</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> left by a reduction in legal support and would likely</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> result in an increase in the number of claims in the longer term</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Grossly exag</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">gerated claims</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Gross exaggeration amounting to dishonesty should of course be treated seriously by the court, where appropriate by way of criminal prosecution</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">However, these cases are seldom as straightforward as tabloid headlines suggest, and care needs </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to be taken to avoid punishing claimants who honestly believe symptoms to be  accident-related but which turn out not to be, or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">those </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">who include in their claim items which are reasonably claimed but are not ultimately awarded by the courts</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Lower premi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">ums</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The savings </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">being </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">achieved </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">by insurers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">as a result of the April reforms are set out above</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (paragraph 7)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We strongly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">believe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that insurers should be given a specific indication of the government’s expectations in terms of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">expected </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">reductions in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">premiums</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The other factors that drive reductions in premiums – </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">g</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> accident frequency, cost of parts – need to be taken into account to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> ensure that all</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> savings are passed on to policyholders</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Insurers should be more transparent in what benefits they are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">passing on to the consumer and for what reason. This will provide additional evidence on the success or otherwise of reforms that are introduced in order to reduce motor insurance premiums.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Strategic  approach</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Consid</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">eration should be given to the C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ourts </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and their handling of cases, and whether a part</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">icular concern is an issue for G</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">overnment or should be left in the hands of the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ourts.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">For example the Competition Commission are looking at issues around hire and repair at the same time as the Court of Appe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">al are due to give a decision on the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Coles v Hetherton</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> case which deals with the same issues (RSA inflating repair costs in non-fault accident).  This decision may well have a bearing on some of the theories of harm identified by the Competition Commission</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Additional Issues</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Information sharing</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We agree consideration should be given to better information sharing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and MASS has been in discussions with the ABI for over two years to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">find </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">agreement on what data can be shared with claimant solicitors at an early</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> stage. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Medical Reports / Accident Information</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This issue touches on topics that are more complex than they initially appear</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">On provision of “details about the accident” to the expert, it may appear obvious that the expert would benefit from being given</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a clear accoun</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t of the accident circumstances; but legally</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> it is not the role of the expert to determine liability; it may be that where the claimant and defendant give radically different accounts of the accident circumstances the expert would benefit fr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">om knowing this, but it is for the court, not the medico-legal expert, to assess which account should be accepted</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Medical records can</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> sometimes assist</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the process</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">; our view is that they should be provided to the expert where the claimant, the defendant, o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">r the expert consider it necessary, but that to require them to be reviewed in every case would simply add cost and delay to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">claims </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">process</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The GMC could undoubtedly play a part in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">auditing reports</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. H</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">owever, our opinion is that this </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">highly specialised</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a would need a specialist, self-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">funded, body to regulate these changes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Collaboration on Fraud</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We have been in discussions with the insurance industry on this issue and are optimistic that we are close to resolving the data sharing issue in order to i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">dentify and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">stop fraudulent claims. The government may wish to set a deadline to encourage this but the parties have put aside their differing views on the way this has been handled so far and hope to have a working model </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">very soon.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Pre-medical Offers</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Ban</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ning pre-medical offers could be brought about by changes in the protocols for cases within and outside of the portal. In our mind, this could simply </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">done by adding a rule that "No damages for injuries should be made without the evidence of a properly a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ccredited medical e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">xpert supporting those injuries"</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Alternatively, if pre-med offers were simply ignored when claims are presented to insurers through the Portal or under any other pre-action protocol, or through the courts, and insurers were required to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">pay the claim in full notwithstanding any payment made under a pre-med offer, the practice of making pre-med offers is likely to stop</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Transparency</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">O</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ne issue on transparency </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">worthy of consideration is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">around the starting of new policies. Our understanding is that when a new policy is created through a ‘broker’ (such as gocompare) the insurer has little opportunity to cancel the policy </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">if there are fraudulent aspects,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> before the expiry of the 14 day canc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ellation period.  We would suggest that this element needs to be investigated further in order to stop fraud at the instigation of the policy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Additional Comments on the Governments Response</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Identity Checks</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> – Whilst many claimant solicitors already unde</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rtake identi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ty checks, MASS agrees that these</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> could be improved and would recommend that the Government holds discussions with the legal profess</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ion and their regulator (SRA) on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> what additional steps would be feasible and practical within the personal injur</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">y sector, bearing in mind that due to the nature of the work, clients are often many miles away from the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ir</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> solicitor.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Enticements to Claim</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> – MASS believes that the Government </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">should undertake tougher </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">action than just talking to the regulators. In order to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> protect the accident victim, all those engaged in handling RTA claims should, we believe, operate under the same rules. Offering enticements could be seen to be encouraging fraudulent or exaggerating claims, as can settling a claim without a medical repor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t. Consequently MASS urges the Government to ensure that the three main regulators address thi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s issue and ensure that the same rules apply to all solicitors, insurers and claims management companies in this respect.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Consumer Education</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> – MASS has always be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lieved that educating the consumer and driver is an important aspect o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">f addressing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the misconceptions of behaviour like uninsured driving and fraud.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In order to ensure that the message is consistent and clear, MASS urges the industry to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">collaborate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> not onl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">y in combating fraud, but to send out a clear message that t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he industry is working together and that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">any </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">fraud</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ulent behaviour</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> will be identified and not be tolerated. Perception</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, as ever</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is key and education will assist to change the publics</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> current perce</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ption that they can ‘get away with it’. MASS would be very happy to work with the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Governmen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t and other stakeholders to better educate the consumer.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Third Party Capture</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> – Action needs to be taken to ban third party capture as well as pre-medical offers. Bo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">th are methods used increasingly by insurers who contact claimants </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">direct to ‘entice’ / persuade them to settle their claim quickly, without being given the opportunity to obtain the full facts of their prognosis or value of their claim from independent le</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">gal advice.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p styl